{{Infobox film | name = Djantoeng Hati | image = File:Djantoeng Hati (1941; obverse).jpg | image size = | border = | alt = | caption = Handbill | director =[[Njoo Cheong Seng]] | producer ={{plainlist| *[[Fred Young (director)|Fred Young]] *SI Liem }} | writer = Njoo Cheong Seng | starring = {{plainlist| *Rr Anggraini *Ariati *Chatir Harro }} | music = [[Koesbini|R. Koesbini]] | cinematography = [[The Teng Chun]] | editing = | studio = Majestic Pictures | distributor = | released = {{Film date|1941|||Dutch East Indies|df=yes}} | runtime = | country = [[Dutch East Indies]] | language = [[Malay language|Malay]] | budget = | gross = }} '''''Djantoeng Hati''''' ('''''Heart and Soul''''') is a 1941 film from the [[Dutch East Indies]] directed by [[Njoo Cheong Seng]]. A tragedy warning against modernity,{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=240}} it starred A Sarosa, Rr Anggraini, and Ariati
==Plot== Two students&nbsp;– the traditional Karina (Rr Anggraini) and metropolitan Roesdjana (Ariati)&nbsp;– are in competition for Karina's husband Sobari (Chatir Harro). Eventually Karina wins out.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=240}}{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djantoeng Hati}}
==Production== ''Djantoeng Hati'' was written and directed by [[Njoo Cheong Seng]]. The film was produced by [[Fred Young (director)|Fred Young]] and SI Liem of Majestic Film.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djantoeng Hati}} It was the company's first production.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=240}} It starred A Sarosa, Rr Anggraini, [[Soerip]], and Ariati;{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djantoeng Hati}} Njoo's wife [[Fifi Young]], who had previously acted in all his films, was unable to act owing to health reasons.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=240}}{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=228–229}} Most of its stars were of noble (''ningrat'') descent, an attempt to draw middle-class audiences,{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djantoeng Hati}} while the story focused on students to draw educated viewers.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=240}}
The [[black-and-white]] film was shot by [[The Teng Chun]], one of Fred Young's friends from when he studied in the United States; The also allowed Majestic to use his studios in Batavia (modern-day Jakarta).{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=239}} The's brother Teng Liong served as [[sound director]]. The film featured seven ''[[kroncong]]'' songs by [[Koesbini|R. Koesbini]] which were sung by the main cast.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djantoeng Hati}}
==Release and reception== ''Djantoeng Hati'' was released in 1941.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djantoeng Hati}} Majestic's second film, ''[[Air Mata Iboe]]'' (''Mother's Tears'') was released later in 1941. It was their last production before the [[Japanese occupation of Indonesia|Japanese occupation]] the following year.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=241}}
''Djantoeng Hati'' is likely a [[lost film]]. The American visual anthropologist [[Karl G. Heider]] writes that all Indonesian films from before 1950 are lost.{{sfn|Heider|1991|p=14}} However, JB Kristanto's ''Katalog Film Indonesia'' (''Indonesian Film Catalogue'') records several as having survived at [[Sinematek Indonesia]]'s archives, and Biran writes that several Japanese propaganda films have survived at the [[Netherlands Government Information Service]].{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=351}}
